<DocsLayout title="References">

<h1>References</h1>

<p class="lead">
This handbook draws on publicly available security research, vendor
advisories, and well-known industry resources. If you want to go deeper
into any topic covered here, these are good places to start.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>Vulnerability Databases</h2>

<div class="ref-grid">

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://cve.mitre.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>CVE (MITRE)</h3>
    <p>The canonical catalog of publicly disclosed vulnerabilities, identified by CVE ID.</p>
  </a>

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://nvd.nist.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>NVD (NIST)</h3>
    <p>The National Vulnerability Database — CVE entries enriched with severity scores (CVSS) and metadata.</p>
  </a>

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://www.exploit-db.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>Exploit-DB</h3>
    <p>An archive of public exploits and proof-of-concept code for known vulnerabilities.</p>
  </a>

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://attack.mitre.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</h3>
    <p>A knowledge base of real-world adversary tactics and techniques used post-exploitation.</p>
  </a>

</div>

<h2>Standards &amp; Guidance</h2>

<div class="ref-grid">

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://owasp.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>OWASP</h3>
    <p>Community-driven resources on application security, including the well-known OWASP Top 10.</p>
  </a>

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://www.cisa.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>CISA</h3>
    <p>The U.S. Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency — advisories and the Known Exploited Vulnerabilities catalog.</p>
  </a>

</div>

<h2>Research &amp; Disclosure</h2>

<div class="ref-grid">

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>Project Zero</h3>
    <p>Google's security research team — deep technical write-ups on real, in-the-wild zero-days.</p>
  </a>

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://citizenlab.ca" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>Citizen Lab</h3>
    <p>University of Toronto research group that has uncovered spyware campaigns including Pegasus.</p>
  </a>

</div>

<h2>Bug Bounty Platforms</h2>

<div class="ref-grid">

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://hackerone.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>HackerOne</h3>
    <p>One of the largest bug bounty and coordinated disclosure platforms, connecting researchers with vendor programs.</p>
  </a>

  <a class="ref-card" href="https://bugcrowd.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
    <h3>Bugcrowd</h3>
    <p>Crowdsourced security platform running bug bounty and vulnerability disclosure programs.</p>
  </a>

</div>

<h2>Case Studies Referenced</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Stuxnet</strong> — Symantec and Kaspersky technical write-ups on the worm's four chained Windows zero-days.</li>
  <li><strong>WannaCry / EternalBlue</strong> — CVE-2017-0144; NHS Digital and CERT-EU incident advisories.</li>
  <li><strong>Heartbleed</strong> — CVE-2014-0160; the original disclosure at heartbleed.com by Codenomicon and Google Security.</li>
  <li><strong>Log4Shell</strong> — CVE-2021-44228; Apache Software Foundation security advisory.</li>
  <li><strong>Pegasus / FORCEDENTRY</strong> — CVE-2021-30860; Citizen Lab's original research report, and Google Project Zero's technical deep-dive.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Suggested Further Reading</h2>

<ul>
  <li><em>The Art of Software Security Assessment</em> — Dowd, McDonald, Schuh</li>
  <li><em>Countdown to Zero Day</em> — Kim Zetter (on Stuxnet)</li>
  <li><em>This Is How They Tell Me the World Ends</em> — Nicole Perlroth (on the zero-day market)</li>
</ul>

